DevOps 100 Days â€“ Day 6: Automate a Cron Job on Linux

Introduction
Today, in my DevOps 100 Days Challenge ðŸš€, I worked on automating a simple task on Linux using cron. Cron is a scheduling utility that lets you run scripts or commands automatically at specific intervals.

The goal for Day 6 was to create a sample cron job on all Nautilus app servers that writes hello into a file every 5 minutes. This is a basic simulation of how system admins automate day-to-day tasks.

Step 1: Connect to the server using SSH
First, I logged into the app server from the jumphost:

ssh tony@stapp01.stratos.xfusioncorp.com
Enter yes to accept the server key.

Enter your password.

Tip: Repeat this for all app servers (stapp01, stapp02, stapp03).

Step 2: Check/Install Cron (cronie)
Check if cron is installed:

rpm -q cronie
If installed, it shows the version.

If not installed, run:

sudo yum install -y cronie
Step 3: Start and enable the cron service
Start cron and make sure it runs after reboot:

sudo systemctl start crond
sudo systemctl enable crond
sudo systemctl status crond
You should see Active: active (running) â€” meaning cron is ready.

Step 4: Add a sample cron job
We want to run a command every 5 minutes that writes â€œhelloâ€ to /tmp/cron_text.

Add the cron job for root using:

echo "*/5 * * * * echo hello > /tmp/cron_text" | sudo crontab -
Verify it:

sudo crontab -l
You should see:

*/5 * * * * echo hello > /tmp/cron_text
Important: Make sure the command is echo (not echp) and the file path is absolute /tmp/cron_text.

Step 5: Test the cron job
Wait 5â€“6 minutes, then check the file:

cat /tmp/cron_text
You should see:

hello
Cron will overwrite this file every 5 minutes automatically. âœ…

Step 6: Repeat on other servers
SSH into stapp02 and stapp03 and repeat Steps 2â€“5. This ensures the cron job runs on all app servers, just like system admins intended.

Key Takeaways
Cron allows automatic scheduling of tasks in Linux.

cronie package provides cron functionality; crond is the service that runs it.

Cron jobs must use absolute paths and correct syntax.

You can automate repetitive tasks on multiple servers efficiently.

